---

<Layout title="Create Your First AI Persona" lang="en" currentPath="/guide/first-persona" description="Learn how to create a custom AI persona with SOUL.md in OpenClaw.">
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="badge badge-orange">Persona Guide</span>
      <h1>Create Your First Persona</h1>
      <p class="page-subtitle">Give your AI assistant a name, personality, and skills. SOUL.md is the file that defines who your AI truly is.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="content-grid">
        <aside class="toc">
          <div class="toc-inner">
            <div class="toc-title">On This Page</div>
            <ul>
              <li><a href="#what-is-persona">What is a Persona?</a></li>
              <li><a href="#create-steps">Create a Persona</a></li>
              <li><a href="#soul-example">Example SOUL.md</a></li>
              <li><a href="#tips">Personalization Tips</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </aside>

        <article class="article">
          <section id="what-is-persona" class="article-section">
            <h2>What is a Persona / SOUL.md?</h2>
            <p>
              In OpenClaw, a <strong>Persona</strong> is the identity of your AI assistant ‚Äî its name, personality,
              communication style, areas of expertise, and behavioral rules. The persona is defined in a special file
              called <code>SOUL.md</code> (a plain text file ‚Äî you can open it with Notepad or any text editor), which lives in your workspace folder.
            </p>
            <p>
              Think of <code>SOUL.md</code> as your AI's "job description" or "work brief" ‚Äî it tells the AI who it is and how to behave. When OpenClaw starts a new conversation,
              it reads SOUL.md and uses it as the AI's instructions (sometimes called a "system prompt" ‚Äî think of it as the AI's work manual) that shapes every response. A well-written
              SOUL.md transforms a generic AI into a specific, consistent personality that feels like a real assistant.
            </p>

            <div class="concept-cards">
              <div class="concept-card">
                <div class="concept-icon">üß†</div>
                <h3>Without SOUL.md</h3>
                <p>Generic AI responses. No consistent personality. Doesn't know your preferences or context. Starts fresh every time.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="concept-card featured">
                <div class="concept-icon">‚ú®</div>
                <h3>With SOUL.md</h3>
                <p>Consistent personality. Knows your name, your work, your preferences. Speaks in a style you chose. Feels like a real assistant.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="info-box">
              <span class="info-icon">üìÅ</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Where is SOUL.md?</strong> By default, it lives at <code>~/.openclaw/workspace/SOUL.md</code>.
                The workspace path is configured during <code>openclaw onboard</code> and can be found in your config file.
              </div>
            </div>
          </section>

          <section id="create-steps" class="article-section">
            <h2>Create a Persona Step by Step</h2>

            <div class="terminal-open-hint">
              üñ•Ô∏è <strong>Open your Terminal</strong> (the command input window) first:
              Mac: press <code>‚åò+Space</code> ‚Üí type "Terminal" ‚Üí Enter |
              Windows: press <code>Win+R</code> ‚Üí type <code>cmd</code> ‚Üí Enter
            </div>

            <StepCard number={1} title="Find your workspace directory">
              <div class="code-hint">‚¨áÔ∏è Copy and paste into Terminal</div>
              <pre><code>openclaw config get workspace</code></pre>
              <p>This prints the folder path ‚Äî something like <code>/Users/yourname/.openclaw/workspace</code>. That's where your SOUL.md lives.</p>
            </StepCard>

            <StepCard number={2} title="Create SOUL.md using any text editor">
              <p>
                <strong>SOUL.md is just a plain text file</strong> ‚Äî you can create and edit it with any app.
                <br/>The <code>.md</code> extension stands for "Markdown" ‚Äî it's a simple text format that any notepad can open.
              </p>
              <p><strong>Easiest options (no coding required):</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Mac:</strong> Open TextEdit ‚Üí File ‚Üí New ‚Üí Format ‚Üí Make Plain Text ‚Üí save as <code>SOUL.md</code></li>
                <li><strong>Windows:</strong> Open Notepad ‚Üí save as <code>SOUL.md</code> (choose "All Files" in file type dropdown)</li>
                <li><strong>VS Code (if installed):</strong> <code>code ~/.openclaw/workspace/SOUL.md</code></li>
              </ul>
              <p>Or create it from Terminal in one command:</p>
              <div class="code-hint">‚¨áÔ∏è Copy and paste into Terminal</div>
              <pre><code>touch ~/.openclaw/workspace/SOUL.md</code></pre>
              <p>Then open it with your preferred text editor and paste in the template from the next section.</p>
            </StepCard>

            <StepCard number={3} title="Write your persona definition">
              <p>At minimum, define these four sections:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Identity</strong> ‚Äî name, role, personality traits</li>
                <li><strong>User context</strong> ‚Äî who you are, what you do, your preferences</li>
                <li><strong>Skills</strong> ‚Äî what the AI is good at and should focus on</li>
                <li><strong>Behavioral rules</strong> ‚Äî how the AI should respond, what to avoid</li>
              </ul>
            </StepCard>

            <StepCard number={4} title="Restart the gateway to apply changes">
              <pre><code>openclaw gateway restart</code></pre>
              <p>OpenClaw reads SOUL.md on startup. After restart, send a message to test the new persona:</p>
              <pre><code>Who are you?</code></pre>
              <p>The AI should now introduce itself using the identity you defined.</p>
            </StepCard>

            <StepCard number={5} title="Iterate and refine">
              <p>
                Building a great persona is an iterative process. Have conversations, notice what feels off,
                and edit SOUL.md to refine it. Common improvements:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Add specific knowledge areas relevant to your work</li>
                <li>Tune the response length (concise vs. detailed)</li>
                <li>Set the formality level (casual / professional / technical)</li>
                <li>Add context about your current projects</li>
              </ul>
            </StepCard>
          </section>

          <section id="soul-example" class="article-section">
            <h2>Example SOUL.md</h2>
            <p>Here's a complete, real-world example. Copy it as a starting point and replace the specifics with your own:</p>

            <div class="code-label">~/.openclaw/workspace/SOUL.md</div>
            <pre><code>---
name: "Alex"
role: "Personal AI Assistant & Dev Partner"
version: "1.0"
---

# Identity

You are Alex, a sharp and reliable personal AI assistant. You're knowledgeable,
pragmatic, and a bit witty ‚Äî you don't take yourself too seriously, but you always
deliver quality work. You communicate clearly and concisely, avoiding unnecessary
fluff.

# About Your User

Your user is a software developer and entrepreneur working on web and mobile projects.
They use TypeScript, React, Node.js, and occasionally Python. They value clean code,
good architecture, and getting things done efficiently. They prefer direct answers
over lengthy preambles.

**Name:** Jamie
**Location:** San Francisco (PST)
**Current focus:** Building a SaaS product for project management
**Preferred language:** English (casual but professional tone)

# Your Skills

- Software development: TypeScript, JavaScript, Python, React, Node.js, SQL
- System design and architecture
- Code review and refactoring suggestions
- Debugging and troubleshooting
- Writing: technical docs, README files, emails, Slack messages
- Research: summarizing articles, comparing options, answering technical questions

# How You Respond

- Be concise. Get to the point quickly.
- Use code examples when relevant ‚Äî always with proper language tags.
- If you're unsure, say so rather than guessing.
- For complex tasks, break down the approach before diving into implementation.
- Prefer bullet points over walls of text for lists and comparisons.
- Use markdown formatting ‚Äî it renders properly in the chat interface.

# What to Avoid

- Don't be sycophantic (no "Great question!" or "Certainly!")
- Don't over-explain obvious things
- Don't add unnecessary disclaimers to every code snippet
- Don't start responses with "I"</code></pre>

            <div class="tip-box" style="margin-top:1.5rem">
              <strong>üí° Pro tip:</strong> The "About Your User" section is gold. The more specific context you give the AI
              about yourself, your work, and your preferences, the more useful it becomes. Don't skip this section.
            </div>
          </section>

          <section id="tips" class="article-section">
            <h2>Personalization Tips</h2>

            <div class="tips-grid">
              <div class="tip-card">
                <div class="tip-num">01</div>
                <h3>Add domain-specific vocabulary</h3>
                <p>If you work in finance, medicine, or a niche field, include a glossary or context section with industry terms and concepts the AI should know.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="tip-card">
                <div class="tip-num">02</div>
                <h3>Define your communication channels</h3>
                <p>Tell the AI where it will be used. "You often communicate via Telegram on mobile ‚Äî keep responses readable on small screens."</p>
              </div>
              <div class="tip-card">
                <div class="tip-num">03</div>
                <h3>Create multiple personas for different roles</h3>
                <p>You can have multiple workspace directories, each with its own SOUL.md. Use one persona for work, another for creative projects, another for personal tasks.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="tip-card">
                <div class="tip-num">04</div>
                <h3>Include your current projects</h3>
                <p>A "Current Projects" section with brief descriptions of what you're working on helps the AI give immediately relevant responses without constant re-explaining.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="tip-card">
                <div class="tip-num">05</div>
                <h3>Set explicit formatting rules</h3>
                <p>Tell the AI exactly how you want output formatted: "Always use TypeScript types in code examples. Prefer functional style over OOP. Use 2-space indentation."</p>
              </div>
              <div class="tip-card">
                <div class="tip-num">06</div>
                <h3>Use it for team personas too</h3>
                <p>On a shared OpenClaw instance, each team member can have their own persona for specialized tasks. See the BlackPink case study for a real example.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </section>

          <div class="nav-buttons">
            <a href="/guide/telegram" class="btn btn-outline">‚Üê Telegram Guide</a>
            <a href="/guide/blackpink-case" class="btn btn-primary">Next: Case Study ‚Üí</a>
          </div>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
